The terrace offered little respite from the relentless onslaught of the storm, its flagstones slick with driving rain, the very air thick with the scent of sodden earth and bruised hydrangeas. A quick scan of the treacherous mud nearest the study door revealed only the uniform pockmarks of the downpour; not a single discernible footprint disturbed the surface. Indeed, anyone who had paused here to "clear their head" would have been drenched to the bone, a condition Julian Thorne had notably lacked. The terrace, it seemed, provided a rather porous foundation for his alibi; perhaps the drawing room might offer a more illuminating conversation, or a re-examination of the study, now that the immediate scene had been surveyed.

